				 World Bank pat for NIT
 OUR CORRESPONDENT																								Durgapur, Nov. 24: The National Institute of Technology (NIT), a deemed university, has been identified as one of the best institutions in the country in terms of utilisation of World Bank funds.																								The World Bank authorities are deeply impressed with the performance of the institution and it will provide more funds for further development, scientist Bikash Sinha, the chairman of the NIT board of governors, said today. 																								Sinha was addressing the third convocation of the institute here, 200km from Calcutta. NIT has already used up the money allotted to it by the World Bank under its Technical Education Quality Improvement Programme (Tequip). 																								The progress of Tequip was lauded by the officials of the World Bank at review meetings. NITs score in the performance audits held by the bank has increased from 6.1 in September 2005 to 8.6 in May 2007, Sinha said.																								The World Bank had identified NIT as a leading institute for implementing projects under Tequip in 2004, according to NIT director Swapan Bhattacharya. The institute was given a lifetime allocation of Rs 21.36 crore. We have erected a state-of-the-art laboratory for engineering students and a language laboratory and started several new workshops using the Tequip funds, Bhattacharya said. 
